  abstract = {Many experiments have demonstrated that some less abundant species, often called keystone species, also have strong effects on communities and ecosystems. Keystone species differ from dominant species in that their effects are much larger than would be predicted from their abundance. Ambiguity in the use of the term keystone and the lack of an operational definition have led to criticism of its continued application in research and policy contexts. In this article we clarify the keystone concept, discuss its relevance to management processes, and suggest additional research that needs to be performed.},
